No sense conjecturing about it, let's see what the data has to say!

Data Wrangling¶

The datasets used for the data analysis project were provided by the Udacity Team. I was able to choose from a set of 5 or 6 datasets, but immediately settled on European Soccer Dataset. This dataset consisted of 7 tables: Country, League, Match, Player, Player_Attributes, Team, and Team_Attributes. This dataset was built like a true database would be, with no repeating information within the tables from other tables, just identifiers, or primary/foreign keys to acknowledge the relationship. In order for my to conduct my analysis the way I would like to, I would have to manipulate a few of these tables extract the information and data I needed.

Here are the SQL scripts that I wrote to access the desired data within the european soccer database I selected to work with.

  1. European Total Goals Table:

    WITH t2 AS (

             WITH t1 AS  (
                     SELECT league_id,
                            season,
                            SUM(home_team_goal) AS total_home_goals_scored,
                            SUM(away_team_goal) AS total_away_goals_scored
                     FROM match
                     GROUP BY 1, 2
                     ORDER BY 3 DESC
                    )
         SELECT league_id,
                season,
                total_home_goals_scored,
                total_away_goals_scored,
                (total_home_goals_scored + total_away_goals_scored) AS 
                 total_goals_scored
         FROM t1
         ORDER BY 5 DESC
       )

    SELECT league_id,

             l.name AS league,
         season,
         total_home_goals_scored,
         total_away_goals_scored,
         (total_home_goals_scored + total_away_goals_scored) AS total_goals_scored

    FROM t2 JOIN league AS l ON l.id = t2.league_id;

2.) European Team Attributes:

  SELECT ta.team_fifa_api_id,
               ta.team_api_id,
               t.team_long_name AS team_name,
               date,
               buildUpPlaySpeed,
               buildUpPlaySpeedClass,
               buildUpPlayDribbling,
               buildUpPlayDribblingClass,
               buildUpPlayPassing,
               buildUpPlayPassingClass,
               chanceCreationPassing,
               chanceCreationPassingClass,
               chanceCreationCrossing,
               chanceCreationCrossingClass,
               chanceCreationShooting,
               chanceCreationShootingClass,
               chanceCreationPositioningClass,
               defencePressure,
               defencePressureClass,
               defenceAggression,
               defenceAggressionClass,
               defenceTeamWidth,
               defenceTeamWidthClass,
               defenceDefenderLineClass
  FROM team_attributes AS ta
  LEFT JOIN team AS t
  ON ta.team_api_id = t.team_api_id;

                   WHEN home_team_goal < away_team_goal THEN 0
                   ELSE 1 END AS home_team_result,
               CASE
                   WHEN away_team_goal > home_team_goal THEN 3
                   WHEN away_team_goal < home_team_goal THEN 0
                   ELSE 1 END AS away_team_result,
        FROM t4
       )

ON fs.team_api_id = t4.home_team_api_id AND
   fs.team_api_id = t4.away_team_api_id;

METHODS SECTION:¶

Data Cleaning, Manipulations & Exploratory Analysis¶

In order to properly analyze and investigate the chosen dataset, I'll need to manipulate it a bit in order to meet the specifications needed to conduct my analysis. Let's take a look at what I did.

To efficiently analyze the the European soccer dataset, I needed to create a few tables from the existing ones in the dataset to make my analysis less cumbersome. Since this soccer dataset is acutally an sqlite database, I needed to download the DB Browser application to help with manipulations.

After assessing my data and its various tables, I concluded that the match table contained the most valuable information for my analysis. So my approach was to start with this table and join/link any other pertinent table to it.

  • Total Goals Scored Table:

For the total goals data frame, I was comparing leagues so I needed the names of the European leagues to compare. I achieved this by joining the league table to the match table at its foreign key, which is the primary key of the league table. Calculating league totals, with regards to goals scored both home or away, was quite easy to achieve in DB Browser, so I just used some SQL syntax to achieve this. Once my total goals table was complete, all I needed to do was import here to Jupyter Notebook for my plotting. I wanted to keep my manipulations in Python to minimum if at all possible, considering the depth of data within this dataset, so I tried to do as much of the manipulations in DB Browser. Considering the length of this project already, I'd have to say that approach didnt really pan out that well, ha ha. That's ok though, I had plenty fun doing it here... and there's so much more to do.

  • Team Attributes Table:

There is a decent amount of attribute data present in the team attributes table, but the attribute I was looking for the most, to compare teams against one another, did not exist: Overall Team Rating. If wanted my analysis to compare teams to one another, I would need to find a way to create this column within the dataset, based on the values assigned to each team. Before I get ahead of myself now, I took a look at the data to see if any Null values were present. Indeed there was, but only in one column: buildUpPlayDribbling. To fill these Null values I took the mean of the column and used Pandas' '.fillna()' to do this.

Now that the dataset is complete with no missing data, I decided to use an algorithm to calculate overall team rating. Being that I am new to Python, I tried to not bite off more than I could chew(coughs) and chose a simple arithmetic function to achieve this: total up all the value of the attributes per team, and divide by the number of attributes to get an average rating, or in this case an 'Overall Team Rating.' I used a lambda function to achieve creating the new column 'overall_team_rating'.

After creating my new column, I ran into another hurdle I wasn't expecting, but should have considering the European soccer dataset spans multiple years: there were multiple ratings for each team, segmented or indexed by season. Since futbol seasons in Europe start in mid-late August and run through mid-May the following year, I decided filter the data by date. First I checked the data type of the 'date' column, which was a numpy object or string. I used Pandas' '.to_datetime()' function to change the data type. Once this was complete, I extracted just the year and used that as the unique values within the 'date' column. But since the column no longer reflected an actual date, I changed the name of the column to 'season' to make more sense to the viewer. Now the data frame is set and ready to plot, all I need to do is filter the dataset by season using Pandas' query function.

  • Fixture Results Table:

I had a lot fun with this data set. This was the most manipulations I have done on a data frame to date, and boy was it challenging, but so rewarding. Because of my spectral obsession with the game, I wanted to create league standing tables for each league and year within the Eurpean Soccer dataset. That's 88 league standings tables.... I unfortunately don't have that kind of time...for this project. I plan on tackling the rest in the future.

For this project however, I decided I would create all the tables and only plot my favorite 3 leagues for the 2008/2009 season. The most efficient approach I found was starting with the fixture results table I imported where columns for home and away team results were created from the existing home team goal and away team goal using SQL. I was able to assign points for either a win, draw or loss respectively with a 3, 1 or 0. Before I started creating my columns for further analysis however, I needed to create conditions for which I could filter Pandas' .groupby() clause by. Here were my conditions:

# home_team cond_1 = fx_df['home_team_result'] == 3 cond_2 = fx_df['home_team_result'] == 1 cond_3 = fx_df['home_team_result'] == 0

# away_team cond_4 = fx_df['away_team_result'] == 3 cond_5 = fx_df['away_team_result'] == 1 cond_6 = fx_df['away_team_result'] == 0

When building my league standings table data frame, I found it easier to calculate all the home team data first and then concatenate that data frame with the away team data frame. I'll use these columns to help aggregate a league standings table for every league and season within the dataset. Here is a list of the columns I created:

  • to save space, I'll show you how I created my aggregated columns for the home team data frame. The away team data
    frame is just a duplication of the code but with away team filters.

    1. hwpt_tot: Home team win point total

      a. This was created by using the .groupby() clause, filtered on condition 1, grouped by league, season, 
     home team api id, and home team, while summing the home team result column using the .sum() method.

    2. hdpt_tot: Home team draw point total

      a. This was created by using the .groupby() clause, filtered on condition 2, grouped by league, season, 
     home team api id, and home team, while summing the home team result column using the .sum() method.

    3. hl_tot: Home team loss total

      a. This was created by using the .groupby() clause, filtered on condition 3, grouped by league, season, 
     home team api id, and home team, while counting the home team result column using the .count() method.

    4. hm_gl_tot: Home team goal total

      a. This was created by using the .groupby() clause, grouped by league, season, home team api id, and home  
     team, while summing the home team goal column using the .sum() method.

    5. hm_gl_cncd_tot: Home team goals conceded

      a. This was created by using the .groupby() clause, grouped by league, season, home team api id, and home 
     team, while summing the away team goal column using the .sum() method.

Once I had this aggregated data for both home and away teams, it was now time to concatenate the two dataframes together. After doing this, I can now create my total points, wins, draws, losses, goals for, goals against and goal differential columns using simple arithmetic between columns. I realized however, every time you create a column, it gets added to the end of the data frame(far right). These columns were the real data I was aiming to depict when taking a glance at the data frame. In order to achieve what I wanted, I had to create a function, 'column_order', which took a data frame and variable or list of variables(column names) you want to reorder, or bring to the front (far left) of the data frame. My league standings table is now complete! Let's plot!

In [89]:
def tm_rtg_pltg_func(df, season):
    
    """
    Function's purpose is to plot the results of the data frame and season passed to it.
    
    Arguments: 
        df - the specified data frame which is a slice of of the team rating data frame by season
        season(str) - the year in which the data is filtered by
    
    Returns:
    A plotted visualization of the specified data.
    """
    season = season
    
    title = "Top Ten Team Performers From Either League For the {} Season".format(season) 
    
    # Creating a matplotlib.axes.AxesSubplot object
    df_fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(17,7))

    # Setting the labels on my matplotlib object
    ax.set_xlabel('Teams')
    ax.set_ylabel('Overall Team Rating')

    df['overall_team_rating'].plot(kind='bar',ax=ax, title=title, legend=False);

# creating a function to order my data frame columns
def column_order(frame, var):
    """
    Function used to order the data frame columns
    
    Returns:
    Based on the selected list of columns, function returns the preferred order list of columns specified.
    """
    if type(var) is str:
        var = [var] # let the command take a string or list
        
    varlist = [w for w in frame.columns if w not in var]
    frame = frame[var + varlist]
    
    return frame

Conclusions:¶

This was a challenging but rewarding project. The purpose of my exploration was to see if I could use the available European Soccer dataset to analytically investigate and possibly answer(while making a few observations along the way) a long standing debate between futbol(soccer) fans:

1.) The 'Age Old Question' among soccer(futbol) fanatics around the globle: Which country has the better league?

Because this is a highly subjective topic to analyze and report on, I thought it would be cool to tackle answering this question from 3 different perspectives, giving my analysis an wholistic approach:

1.) Comparing the goals scored and goals conceded among leagues and teams filtered by season

2.) Comparing team attributes vs. performance

3.) Comparing player attributes/team vs. peformance

Well, firstly I will never concede and admit that I might have bitten off more than I can chew by attempting to investigate this dataset. However, given its size, and the sheer volume of data the set contains, I fear my report has merely touched/skipped the surface of what lies beneath with regards to insight into league, and team peformances per season.

My exploration into the dataset provided me with more questions than answers to my original question; but I think that is a good thing, and expected. That means there's more to explore, more to discover and more to explain. However, with regards to what I had originally set out to accomplish, I would have to say at this point my analysis can not confirm which league is the better league, as there is still way too much analysis left to consider as an influence into performance per season. It's an unfortunate limitation that cannot be avoided for me at this point, as I'm not too familiar with many statistical analysis techniques to give me better insight into the data at a high level. I also did not get a chance to review the player attributes table which I was really looking forward to doing. With that plethera of information as well, further analysis can help determine

For my investigation I was able to tackle the total goals, team attributes, and fixture results data frames respectively. Here is a summation of those explorations:

Total Goals Data Frame:

This subset of data provided some interesting observations which does, to a certain degree, substantiate public opinion about the top 3 or most popular leagues in Europe. Goal scoring creates excitement for the game and its fans, and my resulting visualizations depicted some interesting facts: Of the 8 seasons in total, where goals scored by home teams, away teams and totals per league were calculated, Spain's La Liga BBVA, England's English Premier League and Italy's Serie A finished in the top 3 leagues for most goals scored 6 out of the 8 seasons analyzed. That's pretty impressive, and validates why I hear about these leagues so much. The amount of goal scoring compared to other leagues also validates why I've seen sports networks, like BEIN Sports, or even NetFlix now covers La Liga, Serie A, and even Ligue 1 from France.

As for the top three, I could say the same for the bottom 5, which mixed up a bit here and there but were for the most part the same 5 leagues rounding out the bottom of the table: Portugal's Liga ZON Sagres, Belgium's Juplier League, Poland's Ekstraklasa, Scotland's Premier League and Switzerland's Super League. Portugal and Belgium were systematic 6th and 7th in total goals scored throughout the comparisons per season however in 2013/2014 Belgium's Jupiler League were dead last with only 30 recored goals scored for the season. Something didnt seem right here so I will have to explore that further, but for the purposes of comparisons within my current result set, I left the anomolie as is for now.

Team Attributes Data Frame:

This subset of data provided some interesting observations as well. Based on the total goal results for each league, I was expecting to see a relatively even distribution of teams from each of the top 3 peforming leagues, but that didnt seem to be the case. I at first started to question whether my generic algorithm to calculate overall team rating was sufficient enough to categorically rate each team on par with the given team ratings contained within the original data set, the team attributes table. The 2010 season had Queens Park Rangers as the top peforming team in terms of overall rating but my concerns were alleviated when 2011's season top performers produced Manchester City, as the top performing team that season. They also won the EPL that year which makes sense for their rating, as the EPL is arguably one if not the most physically demanding league in Europe. Through further investigation, it just so happens that 40% of the top ten performers that year also play in Spain's La Liga, with Sevilla FC coming in right behind Manchester City, Athletic Club de Bilbao, RCD Espanyol and UD Almeria. The 2012 season had two representatives from the top 3 leagues, with Stoke City and Sunderland(EPL) peforming in the middle and tail end of the pack. Finally, we get some heavy Italian Serie A and German Bundesliga representation for the 2013 season of top performers with 70% of the field. The 2014 season saw top peformer Italy's Serie A side, Napoli, jump 8 spots to top the top performers for 2014. I might have implied this jump was due to the signing of goal scoring machine Gonzalo Higuain from Real Madrid but it's all conjecture at this point. And lasty, the 2015 season saw another heavy German and Italian representation with 70% of the field.

On that note, given my knowledge of the game, I would have expected to see more well know clubs that perform consistently, year in and year out, having great domestic campaigns as well as faring well in European competitions. Here are a few teams I would have expected to see but didnt: FC Barcelona | Real Madrid FC | Manchester United | Chelsea FC | Aresenal FC | Atletico de Madrid (whose had fantastic European campaigns over the last 5 years) | Juventus and others.

Further analysis, I hope, into the data set will help to explain some of these results. But the more I think about it and view the data, I'm starting to think my algorithm to determine overall team rating, is just a little to rudimentary, and needs to be beefed up a bit.... taking into account player attributes within the team, as well as the team attributes themselves. Further exploration is definitely needed here.

Fixture Results Data Frame:

I had the most fun with this dataset. Manipulating and plotting really presented a challenge but I think I was able to effectively compare multiple variables for each team based on the season selected. Being that I am somewhat familiar with the league finishes of some clubs, it was interesting to see how their stats matched up against one another, specifically total points, wins, draws, losses, goals for and against/conceded. There's still so much more data to explore. As expected however, were the finishes of the top teams in each of the three leagues I decided to plot. For Spain's La Liga, FC Barcelona, Real Madrid CF, and Sevilla FC, England's Premier League, Manchester United, Liverpool FC and Chelsea FC, and for the Italian Serie A, FC Inter Milan, Juventus and AC Milan.

What I did find interesting however, was that for each league more than half of the field of teams had a negative goal differential by the end of the season. With my understanding of the game and leagues, most teams that fall between 7th and 15th places in the league standings consistently are really quite similar. These are usually always the more fun games to watch. There may not be any superstars, or flashy skills, tricks and flare, but they play the game with passion, verve, and tactical discipline. It's clearly evident in the ways these types of matches progress, you can see each team fighting for their existence to remain in the top division -- whereas with some of these other big name clubs with superstars, winning is almost expected. In my opinion, this ruins the spontanaeity of the game. It makes for a better match in terms of end to end action, but for me, like I said before, the game is meant to be played with freedom, creativity and ingenuity, so I enjoy the flare.
